Since, $\sec (\theta-\phi), \sec \theta$ and $\sec (\theta+\phi)$ are in A.P.,
$$
\begin{aligned}
& \therefore 2 \sec \theta=\sec (\theta-\phi)+\sec (\theta+\phi) \\
& \Rightarrow \frac{2}{\cos \theta}=\frac{\cos (\theta+\phi)+\cos (\theta-\phi)}{\cos (\theta-\phi) \cos (\theta+\phi)}
\end{aligned}
$$

